Signal Aggregation Engine (SIG)
1. Purpose of This Document
This document defines the authoritative data model for the Signal Aggregation Engine (SIG).
It specifies:
Canonical signal entities and schemas
Immutable storage rules
Derived aggregate and correlation structures
Decision and provenance linkage
Cross-engine data contracts
This document is the single source of truth for how signals are persisted and referenced.
2. Data Model Principles
Signals Are Immutable — once written, never edited or deleted
Append-Only Processing — new facts create new rows
Explicit Provenance — every signal links to its source artifacts
Derived ≠ Authoritative — aggregates are rebuildable
Version-Bound Semantics — ruleset versions always recorded
3. Persistence Layers
3.1 Raw Signal Capture Store (Optional)
Used for replay and forensics.
3.2 Canonical Signal Store (Authoritative)
Stores normalized, trust-scored signals.
3.3 Derived Stores (Rebuildable)
Stores aggregates, correlation groups, and indices.
